</FONT>
<HR size="1" color="#dedfdf">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
This post details a strategy to achieve a decent amount of damage per pull in a standard exp group and still remain FM at almost all times. Please note this strategy considers the wizard to be medding constantly and using harvest perfectly.  A chart detailing spell combinations and target damage goals based on mob hp and average pull times can be found here :<BR> <A HREF="http://www.dfoster11.homestead.com/files/maxdmgnooom.htm" TARGET=_blank>http://www.dfoster11.homestead.com/files/maxdmgnooom.htm</A> <P>While I was comparing the over all effectiveness of limited chain casting versus casting for maximum spell efficiency I noticed that the damage done but the wizards most powerful nuke at any given lvl often cost too much to be used every fight without going oom. After further examination I also found that the damage done by the wizards most efficient nuke could not be cast in such a way that you can achieve 16% of a mobs hp in damage just by using your most mana efficient nukes. At some lvls the damage done by the wizards best nuke would exceed that 16% mark ( and cost to much mana to be cast in every fight ) or it would only do about 10 to 12% which would mean in order to use this spell it would have to be cast twice ( once again causing the mana cost to reach a point where you will be going oom quite often ).<P>This led me to examine what spells could be used to allow the wizard to achieve a 16% damage ratio at the lowest possible mana cost regardless of spell lvl used. What I found was that in groups with 45 second pull times, at many lvls pre lvl 49 the wizard can achieve 16% damage using lower lvl spells and still be FM at almost all times ( post 49 the wizard can come close to the 16% damage target but he will loose some mana ever pull but the mana loss is not that severe ). This allows the wizard to do a significant amount of damage each pull and still be have enough mana at any given time to burn down a mob in an emergency when needed. This strategy will not permit you to compete with a tank in terms of dps over a one hour time frame, so groups looking to maximize exp gain over time will still be better off with a tank. However if a group needs a wizard to help with the occasional over pull, this strategy should allow you to participate in almost every pull ( unless the group can pull mobs faster than 45 seconds apart ) and still have enough mana to be effective when the over pull comes.<P>Here is the basic strategy. There is a lot of timing involved and you need to determine the average hp of the mobs the group is pulling so it requires that you pay a lot more attention that you usually have to in order to be effective , but wizards sits 90% of the time anyway so what else do you really have to do  <IMG SRC="wink.gif" border="0"><P>1. When you first join the group you must take a guess as to what the average mobs hp is for the area you are hunting ( if you don’t have an idea before hand ask the group what lvl the average mobs they are pulling appear to be ). If your initial guess over estimates the average mobs hp you may find yourself going oom right away because you are over nuking. You are better off under estimating the mobs hp and doing less damage initially until you have a better idea of the average pull times and fight times.<P>2. Next you have to decide what % damage you intend to do per pull. This is based on what clarity buffs you have. If you don’t have any buffs you should never try and do more than 16% of the mobs hp in damage, with clarity 1 you should shoot for 20% and with clarity 2 you should try for 24%. You can pick a spell combination that should achieve this damage ratio by referring to the chart listed at the top of this post.<P>3. Now you must start timing the fights and the average pull times, you can do this using the /time command.  Type /time when the first fight starts and type /time again when the second fight starts.  After you do this about 5 times you should be able to determine the average fight time plus pull time. Once you know this information you can refer to the chart again and pick the best spell combination based on this time. It may not actually be the recommended % damage, if the group has a really short pull time you would do less damage and in a group that has really long pull times you could do more than the recommended %.<P>4. Finally, and this is most important, this strategy is meant to maximize you damage per pull and still leave you almost FM at all times. Because of this you should not cast any support spells ( stuns, snares, roots ), if you do need to cast support spells you will have to lower the damage you do per round as a trade off. If you don’t you will find yourself going oom again.<P>Just a note my chart does not take into account resist for casters or misses for tanks, but unless the mobs your are hunting are highly resistant to the spell type you are using, this should not cause a major difference in your total damage over time.<P>I have been testing this strategy and I have gotten some encouraging paliminarry results with it. If you decide to try this strategy please let me know how it works out for you.
</FONT>
