<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
Ice Comet sucks to be honest. Sure it's a nice idea to throw out 1000+ points in one spell, but it is not as effective as Tears of Druzil. But what spells you are casting, how often and on what MOB's is not what we should be concerned with. Keeping up with the Tanks is too lofty an idea, and sadly we will never EVER be able to do it. I am never OOM during XP camps because I gauge my nuking on how much the Cleric and or Healer is healing. The damage we do inversely effects how much the Healer needs to heal and vice versa. So if at the end of a pull I am at 40% mana and the cleric is at 80% I nuked WAY too much and need to calm down. What I do then is cast the level 20 Stun spell (no nukes) for a few pulls till I catch up with the Healer.<P>Since I am 54 and have access to 2 Draughts now I typically cast them after I drop a Tears of Druzil. There is a method on casting Rain spells that needs to be followed in order to avoid resists. First, Yellow and Reds will be very hard to land Rains on so save them for even con or blues. Also cast the Rain early not later. The more hurt a mob is the more chance they have to resist. I typicall cast Tears when the mob is at 75%, then stun it, followed by a Draught once I am sure the Taunter has control (my Brother is a 53 SK and out taunts level 60 Warriors). Even if Tears is resisted once, that is still 1200 points of damage which is more then Ice Comet and more mana efficient. If (and usually does) all 3 waves hit thats 1800 points for less then IC /drool..<P>So in short, forget keeping up with tanks and instead focus on the Cleric's mana. Use your utility spells more often, and learn when NOT to nuke at all because it just might not be needed.<P>--------------------<P>Baelzharon Hopeslayer<BR>Wizard of the 54th Book of Power<BR>BANG! BOOM! POOF!, Done! "WTF" you looking at? PULL SOME MORE<BR>Member of <BR> <A HREF="http://www.foreverexiled.net" TARGET=_blank>http://www.foreverexiled.net</A>
</FONT>
